For those wondering, she had lost her will to live due to overwork.  This is sadly common in Japan, where it's not unheard of for workers to literally drop dead on the job.  Even though she was free from her job, her issues didn't go away immediately, and she still had depression and burnout.  It's only at the end that she finds the resolve to keep going in her brother, realizing how much they depend on and love each other.  As for why he immediately asked if she was okay, it's because his last memory was of her about to jump in front of a train, not getting hit himself.  It took him a moment to realize where they were do to being in a coma.

Anyway, this is either a dream and the boy died a long time ago, or when she refers to being alone, she means that she's alone because she moved out. The caption "it will just be me from now on" also happens to be on the scene at the airport where she will now literally be on her own. Then, the reason she acts the way she does at the beginning on this, and at the end of the previous chapter, is because she thinks that everything that happened the previous day is too convenient, so she thinks that day was a dream, hence getting prepared to go to work.

2: Shortly after, the sister opens the door to the brother, which means that she was still alive, as the doors of the apartments do not open unless you have the keys (which the brother did not have) or someone does not open from the inside, what happened in this case.  3: This is probably the most important point: the family photo is shown by the brother's POV, in fact if you pay attention, you will notice that on page 27 of the first chapter, the brother is looking at the photo, but as soon as he hears his sister collapsing he runs immediately from her to take care of her, which means that when we review the photo at the end of the story, it is a reminder of the brother, who is happy to be able to be together with his sister and his family.

Unlike these people, I believe that the ending is in reality and not just some kind of sister or brother's dream and that the family photo is also shown to us at the end to give a contrast, I mean, when the photo it is shown the first time the brother is very tense, because he doesn’t know what was going through his sister's head, but when they show it to us again at the end of the story, it is a sort of "memory" of the brother who thinks back to the day when he saved his sister and is happy because he will be able to continue living with her and all their family.  I think so for various reasons: 1: When the brother knocks on the door (which happens before the page where the family photo is shown) the sister calls him on the phone, how would she call him if she was already dead? (2)

Now, there are two types of people, who thinks this doujinshi has a Metamorphosis-like ending and who thinks this has a happy, wholesome ending.  Why do some people believe in the first option?  Because according to them from this moment (https://nhentai.net/g/391780/26/) onwards it's all a sister's dream, which she has while she is dying.  But why do they think it's all a sister's dream from then on?  Because on the page I linked above, that is page 26 of the first chapter, we are shown a photo of their family, which is shown again on the last page of the second chapter.  Others think instead that from the moment the brother arrives in front of the door it is he who begins to dream and thinks he has made it in time, when instead it is not true and the sister is already dead, which is still impossible, because he couldn’t have entered the house if his sister had already killed herself so he couldn’t even see the family photo.
